post_text:
First, I want to thank all of the teachers, staff members, and bus drivers for their dedicated service and keeping our students safe yesterday.

Yesterday afternoon, the Midland School District was under threat of severe weather that might have resulted in a tornado. Because of that, I made a series of decisions to keep our children safe in a way that best served the logistics at the time. While I know that no decision is agreeable to all and no plan is without flaws, yesterday's decision resulted in our one and only goal... To keep kids safe. This will always be the focus of our District as we continue to improve our District and improve our Community.

Dr. Bruce Bryant

MIDLAND ELEMENTARY SCHOOL OPEN HOUSE 2020!!!
Open House will be held at Midland Elementary School on Thursday, August 20th from 5 p.m until 7 p.m. for all Kindergarten through sixth grade students. To maintain the Department of Education guidelines about limiting the number of people in the building and keeping everyone as safe as possible, we are asking that only one parent per family attend Open House. Also, we are asking that all adults and students fourth grade and up wear a mask while in the building.
We are so excited to see our families again! Hope to see you tonight!!!

post_text: In this ever changing environment, our school district is constantly reevaluating its policies as we seek to create the best reentry plan for our students and our community. After guidance from the Arkansas Activities Association, we WILL allow a student to receive virtual instruction while also participating in school athletics. We know that a variety of reasons are factoring into parents' and students' selecting the option of virtual learning, so the District wants to provide as many opportunities as possible to our students while respecting parents' and students' abilities to select what is best for them.

UPCOMING ACT TEST:

Many ACT testing sites have had to undergo a reduction in capacity in order to sufficiently meet the DHS guidelines for social distancing and safety. Some sites have even had to cancel the administration of the test. Because of the reduced capacity and cancellations, some students’ test sites have changed. ACT reports that they sent emails to students using the email address listed in their online profile, We would recommend that you instruct students to login to their ACT online account to verify their test site before test day.

Thank you!

post_text:
Good afternoon. As we move forward in sending out AMI packets for students to work on we are going to make a few changes. Beginning next week, those that pick up meals or have meals delivered will receive their AMI packets at that time. Those that do not participate in the meal program will have their AMI packets delivered to their house beginning Tuesday of next week. We want to minimize the amount of people coming onto campus each day. The AMI packets will be returned to us when students return to school. Please make sure to keep up with the packets until that time. We will also have someone available to answer your phone call and direct it right individual to answer your question from the hours of 9 am to 3 pm Monday through Thursday and 9 am to 12 pm on Friday.

The new AMI packets should be focused on a reading assignment and Math assignment as we continue. We thank you for your patience and understanding and will be reaching out weekly to check on our students and how they are doing.

Below is a message from the AAA
"Due to growing concern over the COVID-19, the AAA will implement a dead period for all member schools starting Tuesday, March 17. During this time, coaches (licensed teacher coaches and registered volunteers) shall be prohibited from engaging in any type of activity involving student athletes whether it be practice, training, weight lifting, tryouts, competition, or travel. Further, school athletic facilities will be closed during the period. On Monday, March 30th, the AAA will release the COVID-19 situation and announce further plans."

post_text: Due to the COVID-19 Virus, Governor Asa Hutchinson has closed all schools in Arkansas beginning Tuesday, March 17th through Spring Break. All Midland Schools will be in session on Monday, March 16th; however, if parents choose to keep their students home, they will be excused. Midland Schools will provide lunches for students at home as well, more details will be sent home tomorrow regarding this. Thank you for your patience and cooperation.

Lysol is awesome and is allowing Kinsa to donate more thermometers. Don’t get left out -- order your free smart thermometer through our school!
Join the 82 other families already participating - Tap this link from your smartphone to sign up: https://get.kinsahealth.com/newUser

Or text the word “FLUENCY” to 555-888 from your smartphone and download the Kinsa app. Follow the directions to order yours.

If you run into any issues signing up, try troubleshooting here: https://support.kinsahealth.com/hc/en-us/articles/360034941752-How-to-get-a-free-Kinsa-thermometer.

Orders close December 13th!!
Let’s spread health this holiday season!

To the Midland Community:
As we continue to improve security for our students and staff, we want to inform you of the upcoming following changes that will begin next Tuesday, October 15th.

We will begin closing and locking the following gates after 8 am:
The gate on Stadium Street,
The gate coming on campus from Hwy.
167 by the Marquee sign
and the gate near the crosswalk.
All vehicles coming on campus after 8 am must enter from the Main Street entrance in front of the high school. All students that arrive late must enter from Main Street and go to the office to sign in.

We apologize for any inconvenience this may have for some but our ultimate goal is to protect our campuses and the students. Mr. Madden will work with the students that must leave early for college or work during the day.

If you have any questions, please feel free to call the office at 501-345-2610 or 501-345-8844.

Thank you.

post_text:
Midland School District General Statement

Midland School District would like to inform our patrons that we have been made aware of a post stating a general awareness statement from the Little Rock FBI office regarding a report they receieved that a school shooting would occur in Arkansas on August 29th. Apparently the reporting party is from another country and allegedly received the information playing an online game. There has not been a specific threat to a particular school in Arkansas. We want you all to know Midland School District takes all such law enforcement announcements seroiusly and will continue to work with our SRO and the Indepence County Sheriff's Office to stay abreast of the situation. We will continue to monitor and take appropriate security measures.

shared_text:
IMPACT Independence County
July 8, 2019 at 5:18 PM ·

DID YOU KNOW….in the early years of life a child’s brain creates over 1 million synaptic connections PER SECOND?! Everything children see, hear, smell, and taste promotes new connections! After the first three years of life, synaptic “pruning” begins to prune back the connections they don’t need and creates “super” highways of communication between the ones they use regularly.

Our IMPACT Excel by Eight (E8) Steering Committee wants to help reinforce the growth of the right connections in our youngest residents! What can we do to help children create a healthy, developed brain?

1. Provide Nutrition
2. Free children from adverse experiences (abuse, neglect, violent environments, etc.)
3. Responsive Interactions

We need your input to move us forward in Independence County! Stop by our E8 booth at the fair July 16th-20th to learn more! Give us your thoughts for a chance to win a prize!

Informational: please read the following.

Public Notice of Application for 21st Century Community Learning Centers Grants
Midland High School is applying for a 21CCLC grant to be able to implement an after-school program at the high school. We need your input as we explore this opportunity further. Midland High School is conducting a needs assessment to determine if an after-school program at the high school would help students be more successful. post_text: If your looking for a school to enroll your child, then search no more. Midland is the school for you. We are a small school which allows us to get to know each child we serve. We offer some of the same advantages as larger schools offer but on a more personalized manner. Our students do very well in competitions: 12 of our 17 participants in the district science fair placed in the top 3 with 8 first place finishes and the overall winner. We also had a student place first in the YES. We offer Advanced Placement Programs, one to one technology for grades 2 and up, and a robust STEAM curriculum. We are the only Lighthouse Discovery Education district in the state utilizing STEAM in Pre-K through 12th grade. In addition, we offer competitive extracurricular activities.There is no time better than today to become a Mustang!!!! Deadline for School Choice is May 1. Applications are on our website at www.midlandschools.org. We would love the opportunity to serve your child and earn your trust.

The link below is to a pdf giving instructions on how to sign up. You may also find this on our website at www.midlandschools.org

https://s3.amazonaws.com/scschoolfiles/104/msd_e-note_how-to.pdf

If you have questions please let us know. If the link does not open please copy and paste in your browser.

Karen Wells is with Dacia Penley Jones.
June 5, 2018 at 9:27 PM ·

This video shows moments of wonder, some sighs of frustration, and then pure joy as our students became #solutionseekers during our STEAM Camp learning experiences and team building exercises. Listen for the questioning that comes with problem-solving, the excitement at figuring out the answer, and - above all - the laughter that enveloped the whole day. I love how our high school and elementary students are helping each other in the learning process. #smallschoolbigheart

post_text: Congratulations to our Lady Mustangs and Mustangs for reaching the state tournament in softball and baseball. Our Lady Mustangs are a 3 seed and will play Wednesday at 2:30. post_text: We invite all parents and patrons to attend our Parent STEAM night to learn about what our students will be experiencing in the classroom. So mark your calendars for April 16th at 6 pm in the high school cafeteria. We look forward to seeing you there.
